David Keatts commented on better supervisor logging: "logging has (mostly) been unified under python's logging module.  if you want something to get logged, just `import logging` and call `<http://logging.info|logging.info>, .debug, .warning, .eror, etc.)`.  logs are stored in /var/log/edhrec and handled by logrotate (which is setup to store backups in S3).  error logs are uploaded to slack live.  there are currently four logs, since the cherrypy logs follow a different format.

two new core modules - logger and watcher.  logger just initializes stuff and is only necessary for application entry points, which currently means api, dynamic and nightly.  watcher is a small script that posts error log updates to slack.

need to tidy up some of the formatting stuff, since it seems like some log messages don't have the asctime/level header, and some are being printed twice.  also need to figure out how to handle batch/ scripts with logging."
attachments.text:
logging has (mostly) been unified under python's logging module.  if you want something to get logged, just `import logging` and call `<http://logging.info|logging.info>, .debug, .warning, .eror, etc.)`.  logs are stored in /var/log/edhrec and handled by logrotate (which is setup to store backups in S3).  error logs are uploaded to slack live.  there are currently four logs, since the cherrypy logs follow a different format.

two new core modules - logger and watcher.  logger just initializes stuff and is only necessary for application entry points, which currently means api, dynamic and nightly.  watcher is a small script that posts error log updates to slack.

need to tidy up some of the formatting stuff, since it seems like some log messages don't have the asctime/level header, and some are being printed twice.  also need to figure out how to handle batch/ scripts with logging.
